'''Edward James Burns''' (born October 7, 1957) is an [[United States|American]] [[prelate]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]]. He is the fifth and current [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Juneau|Bishop of Juneau]].

==Early life and education==
Edward Burns was born in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]], to Donald and Geraldine (n<U+00E9>e Little) Burns; he has a brother, Robert. He attended [[Lincoln High School (Ellwood City, Pennsylvania)|Lincoln High School]] in [[Ellwood City, Pennsylvania|Ellwood City]] and [[Duquesne University]], from where he obtained a [[Bachelor's degree]] in [[philosophy]] and [[sociology]]. He also earned a [[Master of Divinity]] degree and a [[Master of Theology]] degree from [[Mount St. Mary's University]] in [[Emmitsburg, Maryland]].

==Priesthood==
He was [[Holy Orders|ordained]] to the [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priesthood]] by [[Vincent Leonard|Bishop Vincent Leonard]] on June 25, 1983, and then served as [[Curate|parochial vicar]] at Our Lady of Lourdes in [[Burgettstown, Pennsylvania|Burgettstown]] and Immaculate Conception in [[Washington, Pennsylvania|Washington]]. In 1991, Burns was made [[Vocational discernment in the Catholic Church|Vocations]] Director and Vice-[[Rector]] of [http://www.diopitt.org/serves_vocations.php St. Paul Seminary] in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Pittsburgh|Diocese of Pittsburgh]], rising to become full Rector in 1996.

He was also executive director of the [http://www.usccb.org/cclv/ Secretariat for Clergy, Consecrated Life and Vocations] in the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] from 1999 to 2008, whence he was restored to the rectorship of St. Paul Seminary and Pittsburgh's top vocations post.

==Episcopal career==
On January 19, 2009, Burns was appointed the fifth [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Juneau|Bishop of Juneau]], [[Alaska]], by [[Pope Benedict XVI]]. He received his [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|episcopal consecration]] on the following March 3 from [[David Zubik|Bishop David Zubik]], with [[Roger Lawrence Schwietz|Archbishops Roger Schweitz]], [[Missionary Oblates of Mary Immaculate|OMI]], and [[Donald Wuerl]] serving as [[Consecrator|co-consecrators]], at [[Cathedral of Saint Paul in Pittsburgh|St. Paul Cathedral]]. He selected as his episcopal [[motto]]: ''"Pray With Confidence."''

He was formally [[Enthronement|installed]] as [[Juneau, Alaska|Juneau]]'s [[ordinary]] on April 2, 2009, and serves as the spiritual leader of 7,300 Catholics in [[Alaska Panhandle|southeastern Alaska]].

